this is sort of guiding us different portions of the platform that we're

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:18.160
going through. We went through a bunch of them yesterday, and today the next level

00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:21.640
that we're going to go through is Delta Lake and Uniform. So we have a talk on

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:27.280
Delta Lake. That was our agenda a month ago when we put this together, but it

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:33.400
turned out that, you know, we now have acquired company Tabular. So we really

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:36.920
really wanted you to hear from Ryan Blue, the original creator of Apache Iceberg.

00:22:36.920 --> 00:22:41.400
So I want to welcome him on stage and bring him on here.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:55.640
Hey, Ryan. Hey, good to be here. Awesome. Okay, so congratulations. Welcome to

00:22:55.640 --> 00:23:01.520
Databricks. Thank you. We are really excited to be here and also excited to

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:07.520
get started on this new chapter in data formats. Awesome. So what's the main

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:14.079
benefit of joining Databricks? Why join forces? I, you know, I've never wanted

00:23:14.079 --> 00:23:21.319
people to worry about formats. Formats have always been a way for us to take on

00:23:21.319 --> 00:23:27.040
more responsibility as a platform and take responsibilities from people who,

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:31.560
you know, worry about things. When we started this, people were worrying about

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:37.599
whether or not things completed atomically. And so this next chapter is

00:23:37.599 --> 00:23:43.359
really about how do we remove the the choice and the need to stress over, you

00:23:43.359 --> 00:23:49.000
know, am I making this the right choice for the next ten years? That weighs a lot

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:54.079
on people. And I think we just, we want to make sure that everything is

00:23:54.079 --> 00:23:58.319
compatible. That we're all, you know, running in the same direction with

00:23:58.319 --> 00:24:02.599
the single standard, if possible. Hopefully we can get there. Yeah, I think

00:24:02.599 --> 00:24:06.000
we're gonna get there. Actually, you had a talk, right, a while ago that said

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:09.640
something like, I want you to not know about, you know, these formats and

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:13.760
Iceberg. There was some title, right? Exactly. I don't want anyone thinking

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:18.880
about, you know, table formats or file formats or anything like that. That's a

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:24.280
massive distraction from what people actually want to get done in their jobs.

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:30.040
So I want people focusing on getting value out of their data and not the

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:34.760
minutiae. That's the kind of nerdy problem that, you know, I get excited

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:38.719
about. Leave that to us. Hey, I like it. As a nerd, I think it's awesome. We've got

00:24:38.719 --> 00:24:41.760
thousands of people to learn how to do asset transactions and understand all

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:44.160
the underpinnings of the stuff that otherwise would not give a damn about.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:47.920
Okay, well, everybody wants to hear, like, origin stories. So can you tell us a

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:51.479
little bit? How did Iceberg get started? What's the sort of history? Well, at

00:24:51.479 --> 00:24:55.880
Netflix, we were really...

00:24:54.432 --> 00:25:01.432
Talk a little bit about how you came up with the idea of this format, and what was the

00:25:01.432 --> 00:25:02.432
start of history?

00:25:02.432 --> 00:25:03.432
Well, at Netflix, we were really grappling with a number of different problem areas.

00:25:03.432 --> 00:25:08.672
Atomicity was one, that we didn't trust transactions and what was happening to our data.

00:25:08.672 --> 00:25:12.071
We also had issues like, you know, more correctness problems.

00:25:12.071 --> 00:25:16.231
You couldn't rename a column properly and those sorts of things.

00:25:16.231 --> 00:25:22.932
And we realized that the nexus of all of the user problems was the format level.

00:25:22.932 --> 00:25:29.592
We just had too simplistic of a format with the Hive format, and we decided to do something

00:25:29.592 --> 00:25:31.592
about it.

00:25:31.592 --> 00:25:39.952
And then I think the real turning point was actually when we open-sourced it and started

00:25:39.952 --> 00:25:45.292
working with the community, because it turns out everyone had that problem, and we could

00:25:45.292 --> 00:25:48.132
just move so much faster with the community.

00:25:48.132 --> 00:25:49.132
It's been an amazing experience.

00:25:49.332 --> 00:25:53.332
And you started, you were involved in the starting of the Parquet project before that, right?

00:25:53.332 --> 00:25:58.332
Was some of these thoughts even discussed to do this kind of atomicity and so on back there, or no?

00:25:58.332 --> 00:26:05.732
So, part of my experience in the Parquet project informed what we did here, because there were

00:26:05.732 --> 00:26:09.232
several things that just were not file-level issues.

00:26:09.232 --> 00:26:13.332
They were this next level of, you know, really table-level concerns.

00:26:13.332 --> 00:26:17.332
Like, what's the current schema of a table?

00:26:17.332 --> 00:26:20.332
You can't tell that from just looking at all the files.

00:26:20.332 --> 00:26:21.332
Yeah.

00:26:21.332 --> 00:26:24.432
You know, a lot of people think that this is, you know, the first time we're talking

00:26:24.432 --> 00:26:27.332
about these things, you know, you and I and others.

00:26:27.332 --> 00:26:28.332
But this isn't the first time.

00:26:28.332 --> 00:26:31.832
We're actually talking about interoperability and how to make this work, right?

00:26:31.832 --> 00:26:32.832
That's true.

00:26:32.832 --> 00:26:38.432
You know, we've been in touch over the years, you know, talking about this several times.

00:26:38.432 --> 00:26:42.131
I'm glad that we finally got to the point where it made sense.

00:26:42.131 --> 00:26:47.531
You know, I think we were always going and doing our own things, but now we've gotten

00:26:47.531 --> 00:26:53.131
to the point where both formats are good enough that we're actually duplicating effort.

00:26:53.131 --> 00:26:57.131
And the most logical thing to do is this.

00:26:57.131 --> 00:27:03.331
It is to start working together, start, you know, avoiding any duplication if possible

00:27:03.331 --> 00:27:04.331
between the two.

00:27:04.331 --> 00:27:05.331
Yeah.

00:27:05.331 --> 00:27:06.331
That's super awesome.

00:27:06.331 --> 00:27:07.331
Okay.

00:27:07.331 --> 00:27:09.131
So, I think a lot of people here are wondering, what does this mean for the Apache Iceberg

00:27:09.131 --> 00:27:10.131
community?

00:27:10.131 --> 00:27:17.932
Well, I'm really excited because I see this as a big commitment and a pretty massive investment

00:27:17.932 --> 00:27:25.372
in the Iceberg community and the health of both Delta Lake and Iceberg in general.

00:27:25.372 --> 00:27:31.331
I'm very excited, you know, personally to, like, work on this and do a whole bunch of

00:27:31.331 --> 00:27:33.932
fun engineering problems.

00:27:33.932 --> 00:27:35.932
And that'll be really nice.

00:27:35.932 --> 00:27:36.932
Awesome, man.

00:27:36.932 --> 00:27:41.771
So, we're super excited to partner with you, you know, collaborate on Delta, Uniform, Iceberg,

00:27:41.771 --> 00:27:44.892
all these formats, and then, you know, make it such that no one here ever needs to care

00:27:44.892 --> 00:27:45.892
about this ever again.

00:27:45.892 --> 00:27:46.892
Thanks so much.

00:27:46.892 --> 00:27:47.892
Thank you.

00:27:47.892 --> 00:27:48.892
Thank you.

