Okay.

00:27:49.892 --> 00:28:00.652
So, now, as I said, originally this talk was just going to be about Delta.

00:28:00.652 --> 00:28:05.452
So now I want to welcome to stage the CTO of data warehousing at Databricks, Sean Hovsepian,

00:28:05.452 --> 00:28:07.812
to talk about Delta and Uniform.

00:28:07.812 --> 00:28:08.812
Welcome.

00:28:08.812 --> 00:28:09.812
Thanks, Ali.

00:28:09.812 --> 00:28:19.732
And a lot of us, we used to work together with Ryan in the past, and it's really exciting

00:28:19.732 --> 00:28:23.452
to have him here so we can work together again.

00:28:23.452 --> 00:28:27.452
So this talk is going to be very exciting.

00:28:27.452 --> 00:28:29.851
Delta Lake.

00:28:29.851 --> 00:28:39.892
First of all, I'm going to announce the general availability of Delta Lake Uniform.

00:28:39.892 --> 00:28:40.892
What is Uniform?

00:28:40.892 --> 00:28:44.771
Really, it's just short for two words, universal format.

00:28:44.771 --> 00:28:49.252
It's our approach to allow full lake house format interoperability.

00:28:49.252 --> 00:28:54.172
See, with all of these different formats, Delta, Iceberg, Hudi, it's essentially a collection

00:28:54.172 --> 00:28:58.012
of data files in parquet and a little bit of metadata on the side.

00:28:58.012 --> 00:29:03.691
All of the formats use the same MVCC transactional techniques to keep that together.

00:29:03.691 --> 00:29:08.851
And so we thought to ourselves, in this age of LLMs, transforming language left and right,

00:29:08.851 --> 00:29:13.652
couldn't we just find a way to translate that metadata into different formats so that you

00:29:13.652 --> 00:29:18.611
just need to have one copy, and that's exactly what we're doing with Uniform.

00:29:18.611 --> 00:29:24.491
The Uniform GA allows you to essentially write data as Delta and be able to read it as Iceberg,

00:29:25.491 --> 00:29:30.211
And we've worked very closely with the Apache Xtable and Hudi team to make that possible.

00:29:30.211 --> 00:29:33.132
And we're going to be working with the Iceberg team to make that even better.

00:29:33.132 --> 00:29:38.252
The great thing about Uniform is there's barely a noticeable performance overhead.

00:29:38.252 --> 00:29:39.432
It's super fast.

00:29:39.432 --> 00:29:42.372
You get awesome features like liquid clustering.

00:29:42.372 --> 00:29:47.812
There's support for all of the different data types from map, lists, arrays.

00:29:47.812 --> 00:29:51.192
And best of all, it's got a production-ready catalog.

00:29:51.192 --> 00:29:58.312
With UC and Uniform, it's one of the only live implementations of the Iceberg REST catalog

00:29:58.312 --> 00:30:01.991
API, and that's available for everybody using Uniform.

00:30:01.991 --> 00:30:07.652
There have been over 4 exabytes of data that have already been loaded through Uniform.

00:30:07.652 --> 00:30:12.511
We have hundreds of customers using it, and one of them, in particular, mScience, as you

00:30:12.511 --> 00:30:16.611
can see here, was very happy that they were able to have one copy of their data, which

00:30:16.692 --> 00:30:22.372
allowed them to reduce costs and have better time to value.

00:30:22.372 --> 00:30:27.891
And it's innovations like Uniform that are really making Delta Lake the most adopted

00:30:27.891 --> 00:30:29.692
open lakehouse format.

00:30:29.692 --> 00:30:37.891
There have been over 9 exabytes of data processed on Delta yesterday.

00:30:37.891 --> 00:30:41.572
Over a billion clusters per year using it.

00:30:41.572 --> 00:30:43.011
And this is tremendous growth.

00:30:43.011 --> 00:30:44.991
It's 2x more than last year.

00:30:44.991 --> 00:30:49.352
And if you're like me, and when you saw these numbers, I did not believe 9 exabytes.

00:30:49.352 --> 00:30:53.432
I literally, up until yesterday, were going back, looking at the code, making sure they

00:30:53.432 --> 00:30:57.831
calculated it correctly, because it's just a tremendous amount of data every day that's

00:30:57.831 --> 00:30:59.711
going into Delta.

00:30:59.711 --> 00:31:03.671
And it's adopted by a large percentage of the Fortune 500, 10,000-plus companies in

00:31:03.671 --> 00:31:05.951
production, lots of new features.

00:31:05.951 --> 00:31:08.111
But most interestingly, it's sort of that last number.

00:31:08.111 --> 00:31:10.511
There are over 500 contributors.

00:31:10.511 --> 00:31:15.231
And best of all, according to the Linux Foundation, and this is their project analytics site,

00:31:15.231 --> 00:31:21.831
it's open, anyone can go to it today, over about 66% of contributions to Delta come from

00:31:21.831 --> 00:31:24.312
companies outside of Databricks.

00:31:24.312 --> 00:31:31.152
And it's this community that just really makes us super excited and enables a ton of these

00:31:31.152 --> 00:31:33.312
features that are now available.

00:31:33.312 --> 00:31:37.432
And these are time-tested, awesome, innovative functionality.

00:31:37.432 --> 00:31:39.912
Things like change data feed, log compaction.

00:31:40.312 --> 00:31:43.231
I love the row IDs feature that just came out.

00:31:43.231 --> 00:31:45.152
But there are things like deletion vectors.

00:31:45.152 --> 00:31:50.912
Deletion vectors are a way that allow you to do fast updates and DML to your data.

00:31:50.912 --> 00:31:55.752
In many cases, it's 10 times faster than merge used to be.

00:31:55.752 --> 00:32:01.551
So if you have DBT workloads or you're doing lots of operational changes to data, deletion

00:32:01.551 --> 00:32:03.072
vectors make your life easier.

00:32:03.072 --> 00:32:08.752
And there have been over 100 trillion row rewrites that have been saved because of these

00:32:08.752 --> 00:32:10.391
deletion vector features.

00:32:10.391 --> 00:32:14.671
And it's enabled by default for all Databricks users.

00:32:14.671 --> 00:32:20.231
And so it's through these features that we've also been able to unlock access to this amazing

00:32:20.231 --> 00:32:23.312
ecosystem of tools that support Delta.

00:32:23.312 --> 00:32:29.352
And with Uniform, that's now GA, we're able to get the same access to the Hudi and Iceberg

00:32:29.352 --> 00:32:30.352
ecosystem.

00:32:30.352 --> 00:32:35.551
So if you have tools and SDKs, applications that work in there, they're all part of the

00:32:35.551 --> 00:32:38.991
Delta family now, thanks to Uniform.

00:32:38.991 --> 00:32:44.111
And there's been some great improvements to a lot of the connectors, the Trino, Rust connector,

00:32:44.111 --> 00:32:45.872
lots of awesome innovation happening here.

00:32:45.872 --> 00:32:50.231
And a lot of that is thanks to this new thing that we've developed called Delta Kernel.

00:32:50.231 --> 00:32:55.072
Essentially, at the core of all of this, there's a small library that you can just plug and

00:32:55.072 --> 00:33:00.752
play into your applications or SDKs that contains all the logic for the Delta formats, all the

00:33:00.752 --> 00:33:06.111
version changes, new features, and it's making it so much easier for people to integrate

00:33:06.111 --> 00:33:10.271
and adopt Delta, and most importantly, stay up to date with the latest features.

00:33:10.271 --> 00:33:11.271
And we've been seeing this.

00:33:11.271 --> 00:33:15.872
The Delta Rust connector is community supported and has amazing traction.

00:33:15.872 --> 00:33:21.511
Just a few weeks ago at Google's I-O conference, I believe, BigQuery introduced complete support

00:33:21.511 --> 00:33:22.632
for Delta.

00:33:22.632 --> 00:33:27.952
And very recently, DuckDB added full support for Delta.

00:33:27.952 --> 00:33:35.832
And the best part of this is we have Hannes here, who's the co-founder, one of the co-creators

00:33:35.832 --> 00:33:40.312
of DuckDB, CEO of DuckDB Labs, professor of computer science, who's going to talk to us

00:33:40.312 --> 00:33:43.471
a little bit about how they integrated Delta into DuckDB.

00:33:43.471 --> 00:33:45.471
Hannes, get over here.

00:33:45.471 --> 00:33:46.471
Hey.

00:33:46.471 --> 00:33:49.471
Thank you so much.

00:33:49.471 --> 00:33:57.991
Yes, hello and very good morning.

00:33:57.991 --> 00:33:59.752
It's wonderful to see all of you here.

00:33:59.752 --> 00:34:03.551
I have to adjust my eyes a bit to the amount of people.

00:34:03.551 --> 00:34:06.551
As Shanta said, I'm one of the people behind DuckDB.

00:34:06.551 --> 00:34:10.952
So for those of you who do not know what is DuckDB, it's a small in-process analytical

00:34:10.952 --> 00:34:17.471
data management system, speaks SQL, has zero dependencies, and I'm having a lot of fun

00:34:17.471 --> 00:34:21.712
working on it with a growing team.

00:34:21.712 --> 00:34:26.111
And last year, I talked about DuckDB on this very stage for the first time.

00:34:26.111 --> 00:34:27.911
And it was very exciting.

00:34:27.911 --> 00:34:31.392
But also lots of things have happened since then in DuckDB land.

00:34:31.392 --> 00:34:34.632
There's been an incredible growth in adoption for DuckDB.

00:34:34.632 --> 00:34:36.812
We're seeing all sorts of crazy things.

00:34:36.812 --> 00:34:42.851
And here, as an example, it's just the stars on GitHub have doubled within a year to almost

00:34:42.851 --> 00:34:43.851
20,000.

00:34:43.851 --> 00:34:45.651
And in fact, we're so close to 20,000.

00:34:45.651 --> 00:34:50.411
So if you want to like it today, then maybe we'll beat it.

00:34:50.411 --> 00:34:55.252
But what also happened, and just last week, we actually released DuckDB 1.0.

00:34:55.252 --> 00:34:57.291
And that was a big moment for us.

00:34:57.291 --> 00:35:02.772
It was the culmination of six years of R&D in data management systems.

00:35:02.772 --> 00:35:05.332
And what does 1.0 mean?

00:35:05.332 --> 00:35:10.411
That means that we have now a stable SQL dialect and various APIs.

00:35:10.411 --> 00:35:14.272
And most importantly, our storage format for DuckDB is going to be backwards compatible

00:35:14.272 --> 00:35:17.572
from now on out.

00:35:17.572 --> 00:35:23.812
But maybe taking a little bit of a step back, how does DuckDB fit into a general ecosystem?

00:35:23.812 --> 00:35:30.291
If you look at the world's most widely used data tools, Excel, and we look at a very capable

00:35:30.291 --> 00:35:33.491
system like Spark, there's still a pretty big gap.

00:35:33.491 --> 00:35:38.491
There's a lot of data sets that are not going to work in Excel, but they are maybe a bit

00:35:38.491 --> 00:35:40.772
too small to actually throw Spark at them.

00:35:40.772 --> 00:35:46.351
So DuckDB is really perfect for this last mile of data analysis, where you may not need

00:35:46.351 --> 00:35:49.932
a whole data center to compute something.

00:35:49.932 --> 00:35:54.132
So for example, you have already gone through your log files in Spark.

00:35:54.132 --> 00:36:00.452
And now it's time to do some last mile analysis with DuckDB, doing some plots, what have you.

00:36:00.452 --> 00:36:03.111
That's where DuckDB fits into this big picture.

00:36:03.111 --> 00:36:08.671
But now we have to somehow get the data from Spark to DuckDB.

00:36:08.671 --> 00:36:09.671
So how are we going to do that?

00:36:09.671 --> 00:36:14.031
Obviously, we're going to use the best tool for the job available, right?

00:36:14.031 --> 00:36:17.651
CSV files.

00:36:17.651 --> 00:36:18.872
Maybe not.

00:36:18.872 --> 00:36:21.512
So typically, people use Parquet files for this.

00:36:21.512 --> 00:36:26.351
Obviously, both Spark and DuckDB can read and write Parquet files, so that works really

00:36:26.351 --> 00:36:27.351
well.

00:36:27.351 --> 00:36:31.512
But we've all heard about the issues that have appeared with updates and schema evolution,

00:36:31.512 --> 00:36:34.952
these kind of things, which is why we have Lakehouse formats.

00:36:34.952 --> 00:36:40.072
So today, we are announcing official DuckDB support for Delta Lake.

00:36:40.072 --> 00:36:43.911
It's going to be available completely out of the box with zero configuration or anything

00:36:43.911 --> 00:36:46.231
like that.

00:36:46.231 --> 00:36:48.432
But we have done a bunch of these integrations.

00:36:48.432 --> 00:36:52.832
And one thing that's really special about the Delta Lake integration is that we use

00:36:52.832 --> 00:36:57.351
this Delta kernel that Databricks is building with the community.

00:36:57.351 --> 00:37:01.812
And that's really exciting because it means that we don't have to build this from scratch

00:37:01.812 --> 00:37:06.372
like we used to, for example, with the Parquet reader, but we can actually delegate a lot

00:37:06.372 --> 00:37:12.351
of the hard work of reading Delta files to the Delta kernel while at the same time keeping

00:37:12.351 --> 00:37:15.832
our operators within the engine and so on and so forth.

00:37:15.832 --> 00:37:18.351
So it's really exciting.

00:37:18.351 --> 00:37:25.231
We also made an extension for DuckDB that can talk to the Unity catalog.

00:37:25.231 --> 00:37:30.512
So with this extension, we can find the Delta Lake tables in the catalog and then actually

00:37:30.512 --> 00:37:32.971
interact with them from DuckDB itself.

00:37:32.971 --> 00:37:37.312
So here we can see a script that actually works if you install DuckDB now.

00:37:37.312 --> 00:37:40.752
You can install this Unity catalog extension.

00:37:40.752 --> 00:37:43.471
You can create your secret, which is like credentials.

00:37:43.471 --> 00:37:48.272
And then you can basically just read these tables as if they were local tables.

00:37:48.272 --> 00:37:52.111
If you want to hear more about this, there's actually going to be a talk this afternoon

00:37:52.111 --> 00:37:53.952
at 1.40.

00:37:53.952 --> 00:37:57.551
Just look for DuckDB in the title.

00:37:57.551 --> 00:38:01.632
So the Delta extension joins this growing list of DuckDB extensions.

00:38:01.632 --> 00:38:06.791
For example, there's others for Iceberg, Vector Search, Spatial, and this sort of thing.

00:38:06.791 --> 00:38:11.791
But as an open source project and a small team, we're really excited about Tabular and

00:38:11.791 --> 00:38:16.512
Databricks bringing Delta Lake and Iceberg closer together because for us, it means we

00:38:16.512 --> 00:38:21.252
don't have to maintain two different things for the same, essentially, problem.

00:38:21.252 --> 00:38:22.731
And we're really excited about that.

00:38:22.731 --> 00:38:25.572
It means less work for us, and I think everyone wins.

00:38:25.572 --> 00:38:32.031
I just want to plug one sort of small thing that we're actually launching today.

00:38:32.031 --> 00:38:34.012
I've mentioned extensions to DuckDB.

00:38:34.012 --> 00:38:37.272
We've seen a lot of uptake in DuckDB extensions.

00:38:37.272 --> 00:38:42.151
And from now on, actually, we are launching community extensions, which means that everyone

00:38:42.151 --> 00:38:46.491
can make DuckDB extensions and basically publish them and then installing them is as easy as

00:38:46.491 --> 00:38:50.551
just typing install into a DuckDB near you.

00:38:50.551 --> 00:38:52.392
So that's all for today.

00:38:52.392 --> 00:38:53.392
Thank you very much.

00:38:53.392 --> 00:38:56.512
And I will give back to Sjoerd.

00:38:56.512 --> 00:39:03.671
That integration is super awesome.

00:39:03.671 --> 00:39:06.632
It's very exciting.

00:39:06.632 --> 00:39:11.952
So how do we top that?

00:39:11.952 --> 00:39:13.031
By not going back.

00:39:13.031 --> 00:39:14.772
By going forward.

00:39:14.772 --> 00:39:19.231
And forward to Delta 4.0.

00:39:19.312 --> 00:39:22.411
So we have the branch cut.

00:39:22.411 --> 00:39:23.752
It's available.

00:39:23.752 --> 00:39:28.272
Delta 4.0 is the biggest change in Delta since history.

00:39:28.272 --> 00:39:32.111
It's jam-packed with new features and functionality.

00:39:32.111 --> 00:39:37.471
Things like coordinated commits, collations, all sorts of new functionality that make it

00:39:37.471 --> 00:39:41.192
easier to work with, various different types of data sets.

00:39:41.192 --> 00:39:45.192
We won't have time to go through all of this, so I'm going to pick a couple and dive into

00:39:45.192 --> 00:39:48.351
why these are such amazing features.

00:39:48.351 --> 00:39:53.671
So Liquid Clustering is generally available now as part of Delta 4.0.

00:39:53.671 --> 00:39:57.712
And with Liquid Clustering, we really wanted to set out to solve this challenge that so

00:39:57.712 --> 00:39:59.591
many people have brought up.

00:39:59.591 --> 00:40:02.991
Partitioning, it's good for performance, but it's so complicated.

00:40:02.991 --> 00:40:06.512
You get over-partitioning, small files, you pick the wrong thing.

00:40:06.512 --> 00:40:09.432
It's a pain to resolve.

00:40:09.432 --> 00:40:15.632
And Liquid solves this with a novel data layout strategy that's so easy to use that we hope

00:40:15.632 --> 00:40:19.111
all of you will say goodbye to partitioned by.

00:40:19.111 --> 00:40:25.791
You never need to say that again when you define a table.

00:40:25.791 --> 00:40:31.851
Not only is it easy to use, we found out it's up to 7 times faster for writes and 12x faster

00:40:31.851 --> 00:40:32.851
for reads.

00:40:32.851 --> 00:40:36.712
So the performance benefits are amazing.

00:40:36.712 --> 00:40:42.231
And of course, it's easy to evolve the schema, make changes, define anything without having

00:40:42.231 --> 00:40:45.372
to worry about all your data being rewritten and transformed.

00:40:46.111 --> 00:40:50.171
There are about 1,500 people, customers, actively using this.

00:40:50.171 --> 00:40:52.692
The adoption has been insane.

00:40:52.692 --> 00:40:55.971
Over 1.2 zettabytes of data have been skipped.

00:40:55.971 --> 00:40:57.531
And you don't have to take my word for it.

00:40:57.531 --> 00:41:02.332
Even Shell, when they started using it for their time series workloads, saw over an order

00:41:02.332 --> 00:41:04.731
of magnitude improvement in performance.

00:41:04.731 --> 00:41:06.971
And it was just so easy to use.

00:41:06.971 --> 00:41:10.411
Next, open variant data type.

00:41:10.411 --> 00:41:12.332
And this one's really important.

00:41:12.332 --> 00:41:15.012
That first word, open, is really exciting.

00:41:15.012 --> 00:41:20.812
So what happens is now in this world of AI, you have more and more semi-structured text

00:41:20.812 --> 00:41:27.731
data, alternative data sources, all of this coming into the lake house.

00:41:27.731 --> 00:41:31.812
And we wanted to come up with a way to make it easier for people to store and work with

00:41:31.812 --> 00:41:34.752
these types of data in Delta.

00:41:34.752 --> 00:41:38.812
And usually what happens is when you're stuck with semi-structured data, most of the data

00:41:38.812 --> 00:41:42.332
engineers, they sort of have to make a compromise.

00:41:43.291 --> 00:41:44.971
None of us like to make compromises.

00:41:44.971 --> 00:41:48.971
But usually, it's about being open, flexible, or fast.

00:41:48.971 --> 00:41:51.812
And often, they'd only be able to pick two out of these three.

00:41:51.812 --> 00:41:54.611
So for example, for semi-structured data, one approach is just store everything

00:41:54.611 --> 00:41:55.692
as a string.

00:41:55.692 --> 00:41:56.651
That's open.

00:41:56.651 --> 00:41:58.932
It gives you tons of flexibility.

00:41:58.932 --> 00:42:01.452
But parsing strings is slow.

00:42:01.452 --> 00:42:04.812
Why would you store a number as a string and have to reread it every time?

00:42:04.812 --> 00:42:09.452
So of course, there's an option to pick the fields out of your semi-structured data,

00:42:09.452 --> 00:42:12.852
make them concrete types, and you get amazing performance.

00:42:12.852 --> 00:42:15.492
This is open, very fast to access.

00:42:15.492 --> 00:42:18.371
However, if you have sparse data, you sort of

00:42:18.371 --> 00:42:22.251
lose out on a lot of that flexibility to modify the schema.

00:42:22.251 --> 00:42:28.092
And relational databases for a while have had special enum or variant data types.

00:42:28.092 --> 00:42:30.371
But all of those had always been proprietary.

00:42:30.371 --> 00:42:34.251
If you wanted to use them to get a balance of not having to store everything

00:42:34.251 --> 00:42:38.812
as a string and not having to shard out every single column, you got locked in.

00:42:39.171 --> 00:42:42.291
So that's why we're very excited with variants

00:42:42.291 --> 00:42:44.732
to be able to get that sweet spot in the middle.

00:42:44.732 --> 00:42:47.291
You can have your JSON data, store it with flexibility,

00:42:47.291 --> 00:42:50.051
fully open with amazing performance.

00:42:50.051 --> 00:42:51.411
It's very easy to use.

00:42:51.411 --> 00:42:53.852
It works with even complex JSON.

00:42:53.852 --> 00:42:55.891
Here's an example of the syntax.

00:42:55.891 --> 00:43:00.812
And we found, of course, it's eight times faster than storing your JSON data

00:43:00.812 --> 00:43:01.932
as raw strings.

00:43:01.932 --> 00:43:03.852
This is just tremendous.

00:43:03.852 --> 00:43:08.371
So if you're storing JSON in a string field today,

00:43:08.371 --> 00:43:12.051
go back to work or home and start using Variant.

00:43:12.051 --> 00:43:14.651
It's available in DBR 15.3.

00:43:14.651 --> 00:43:17.891
But most importantly, all of the code for Variant

00:43:17.891 --> 00:43:21.011
is already checked in to Apache Spark.

00:43:21.011 --> 00:43:24.592
There's a common subdirectory in the 4.0 branch

00:43:24.592 --> 00:43:26.972
right now that has all of the implementation

00:43:26.972 --> 00:43:29.411
details for Variant and all of the operators.

00:43:29.411 --> 00:43:33.572
And there is a binary format code definition and library

00:43:33.572 --> 00:43:35.932
that we've made available open source so all the other data

00:43:35.932 --> 00:43:37.852
engines can also use Variant.

00:43:37.852 --> 00:43:41.531
We really want this to be an official open format

00:43:41.531 --> 00:43:43.651
that everyone adopts so that, finally, we

00:43:43.651 --> 00:43:46.852
have a non-proprietary way of storing semi-structured data

00:43:46.852 --> 00:43:48.531
reliably.

00:43:48.531 --> 00:43:52.572
And so with that, yeah, it's a big deal.

00:43:52.572 --> 00:43:55.612
With that, I just want to summarize Delta Lake 4.0.

00:43:55.612 --> 00:43:56.531
It's interoperable.

00:43:56.531 --> 00:44:00.452
We have this amazing ecosystem of people like Hannes working together,

00:44:00.452 --> 00:44:01.891
making it better and stronger.

00:44:01.891 --> 00:44:04.151
We get amazing performance benefits.

00:44:04.151 --> 00:44:07.171
And all of this is just so much easier to use now

00:44:07.171 --> 00:44:09.452
than it ever was before.

00:44:09.452 --> 00:44:10.671
OK.

00:44:10.671 --> 00:44:11.171
Thank you.

