01:43:41.891 --> 01:43:46.372
to declare, hey, Python is a first class language of Spark.

01:43:46.372 --> 01:43:51.372
So I'll talk about the other two problems, version upgrades, dependency management, and

01:43:51.372 --> 01:43:55.252
JVM language.

01:43:55.252 --> 01:44:00.771
Now let me dive into a little bit more about why this problem exists.

01:44:00.771 --> 01:44:05.972
So the way Spark is designed is that all the Spark application you write, your ETL

01:44:05.972 --> 01:44:11.291
pipelines, your data science analysis tools, your notebook logic that's running, runs in

01:44:11.291 --> 01:44:16.412
a single monolithic process called a driver that includes all the core server sides of

01:44:16.412 --> 01:44:17.412
Spark as well.

01:44:17.412 --> 01:44:22.771
So all the applications actually don't run on whatever clients or servers they independently

01:44:22.771 --> 01:44:23.771
run on.

01:44:23.771 --> 01:44:26.932
They run in the same monolithic server cluster.

01:44:26.932 --> 01:44:32.051
And this is really sort of the essence of the problem, because one, all of this, because

01:44:32.051 --> 01:44:35.932
they all run in the same process, the applications have to share the same dependency.

01:44:35.932 --> 01:44:39.652
And not only do they share the same dependency as each other, they share the same dependency

01:44:39.652 --> 01:44:42.051
as Spark itself.

01:44:42.051 --> 01:44:45.372
Debugging is difficult, because in order to attach a debugger, you have to attach the

01:44:45.372 --> 01:44:48.932
very process that runs all of those things.

01:44:48.932 --> 01:44:53.331
And now, last but not least, if you want to upgrade Spark, you have to upgrade the server

01:44:53.331 --> 01:44:57.451
and you have to upgrade every single application running on the server in one shot.

01:44:57.451 --> 01:44:58.812
It's all nothing.

01:44:58.812 --> 01:45:03.932
And this is a very difficult thing to do when they're all tightly coupled.

01:45:03.932 --> 01:45:10.051
So two years ago at this very conference, Martin and I introduced to you Spark Connect.

01:45:10.051 --> 01:45:13.051
The idea of Spark Connect is, again, very, very simple at a high level.

01:45:13.051 --> 01:45:19.572
We wanted to take the DataFrame and SQL API of Spark that's either Python or Scala-centric

01:45:19.812 --> 01:45:25.532
and create a language-agnostic binding for it based on gRPC and Apache Arrow.

01:45:25.532 --> 01:45:30.051
And this sounds like a very small change, because it's just introducing a new language

01:45:30.051 --> 01:45:34.891
binding and a new API, language-agnostic, but really it's the largest architectural

01:45:34.891 --> 01:45:40.092
change to Spark since the introduction of DataFrame's APIs themselves.

01:45:40.092 --> 01:45:47.491
And with this language-agnostic API, now everything else runs as clients connecting to the language-agnostic

01:45:47.491 --> 01:45:48.491
API.

01:45:48.491 --> 01:45:53.291
So we're breaking down that monolith into, you can think of it as microservices running

01:45:53.291 --> 01:45:55.211
everywhere.

01:45:55.211 --> 01:45:58.211
And how does that impact end-to-end applications?

01:45:58.211 --> 01:46:03.932
Well, different applications now will actually run as clients connecting to the server, but

01:46:03.932 --> 01:46:05.211
they are really clients.

01:46:05.211 --> 01:46:08.532
They're running in their own sort of isolated environment.

01:46:08.532 --> 01:46:14.692
And this makes upgrade super easy, because the language binding is designed to be language-agnostic

01:46:14.692 --> 01:46:18.132
and forward and backward compatible from API perspective.

01:46:18.132 --> 01:46:24.252
So you could actually upgrade the Spark server side, say from Spark 3.5 to Spark 4.0, without

01:46:24.252 --> 01:46:27.852
upgrading any of the individual applications themselves.

01:46:27.852 --> 01:46:33.652
And then you can upgrade the applications one by one as you like at your own pace.

01:46:33.652 --> 01:46:34.652
Same thing with debuggability.

01:46:34.652 --> 01:46:38.972
Now you can attach the debugger to that individual application that runs in a separate process

01:46:38.972 --> 01:46:46.491
anywhere you want without impacting the server, without impacting the rest of the applications.

01:46:46.491 --> 01:46:51.171
Now for all of the language developers out there, this language-agnostic API makes it

01:46:51.171 --> 01:46:54.572
substantially easier to be building new languages.

01:46:54.572 --> 01:47:00.132
Just in the last few months alone, we have seen community projects that build Go bindings,

01:47:00.132 --> 01:47:03.092
Rust bindings, C Sharp bindings, all of this.

01:47:03.092 --> 01:47:08.291
And it can be built entirely outside the project with their own release cadence.

01:47:08.291 --> 01:47:13.771
So one of the most popular programming languages, probably the top two programming languages

01:47:13.771 --> 01:47:17.972
for data science are R and Python.

01:47:17.972 --> 01:47:19.611
Spark has built-in Python support.

01:47:19.611 --> 01:47:22.211
There's also built-in R support called Spark R.

